                <section class=3D"box-objectives">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Outcomes"></span><h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"l=
t-icon-default">Outcomes</span></h5>

<ol start=3D"1" style=3D"list-style-type: upper-alpha;">
    <li class=3D"lt-math-21265">Compute the dot product of vectors, and use=
 this to compute vector projections.</li>
</ol>
</div></section>

<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section" id=
=3D"section_1"><span id=3D"The_Dot_Product"></span><h2 class=3D"lt-math-212=
65 editable">The Dot Product</h2>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">There are two ways of multiplying vectors which =
are of great importance in applications. The first of these is called the <=
strong>dot product</strong>. When we take the dot product of vectors, the r=
esult is a scalar. For this reason, the dot product is also called the <str=
ong>scalar product</strong> and sometimes the <strong>inner product</strong=
>. The definition is as follows.</p>

<section class=3D"box-definition">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Definition_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B1.7D.5C):_Dot_Product"></span><h5 cla=
ss=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-icon-default">Definition \(\Pa=
geIndex{1}\): Dot Product <a name=3D"def%3Adotproductdefn"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Let \(\vec{u},\vec{v}\) be two vectors in \(\mat=
hbb{R}^{n}\). Then we define the <strong>dot product</strong> \(\vec{u}\bul=
let \vec{v}\) as \[\vec{u}\bullet \vec{v} =3D \sum_{k=3D1}^{n}u_{k}v_{k}\no=
number \]</p>
</div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">The dot product \(\vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}\) is so=
metimes denoted as \((\vec{u},\vec{v})\) where a comma replaces \(\bullet\)=
. It can also be written as \(\left\langle \vec{u},\vec{v}\right\rangle\). =
If we write the vectors as column or row matrices, it is equal to the matri=
x product \(\vec{v}\vec{w}^{T}\).</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Consider the following example.</p>

<section class=3D"box-example">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Example_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B1.7D.5C):_Compute_a_Dot_Product"></span>=
<h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-icon-default">Example \=
(\PageIndex{1}\): <span>Compute a Dot </span>Product <a name=3D"exa%3Adotpr=
oduct"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Find \(\vec{u} \bullet \vec{v}\) for \[\vec{u} =
=3D \left[ \begin{array}{r} 1 \\ 2 \\ 0 \\ -1 \end{array} \right], \vec{v} =
=3D \left[ \begin{array}{r} 0 \\ 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{array} \right]\nonumber \=
]</p>

<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Solution"></span><h6 class=3D"lt-math-21265 editable">Solution</h6>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">By <a title=3D"4.7: The Dot Product" class=3D"mt=
-self-link" href=3D"https://math.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/=
A_First_Course_in_Linear_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3A_R/4.07%3A_The_Dot_Product#=
def:dotproductdefn" rel=3D"internal">Definition \(\PageIndex{1}\)</a>, we m=
ust compute \[\vec{u}\bullet \vec{v} =3D \sum_{k=3D1}^{4}u_{k}v_{k}\nonumbe=
r \]</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">This is given by \[\begin{aligned} \vec{u} \bull=
et \vec{v} &amp;=3D (1)(0) + (2)(1) + (0)(2) + (-1)(3) \\ &amp;=3D 0 + 2 + =
0 + -3 \\ &amp;=3D -1\end{aligned}\]</p>
</div></div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">With this definition, there are several importan=
t properties satisfied by the dot product.</p>

<section class=3D"box-definition">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Proposition_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B1.7D.5C):_Properties_of_the_Dot_Prod=
uct"></span><h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-icon-defaul=
t">Proposition \(\PageIndex{1}\): <span>Properties of the Dot </span>Produc=
t <a name=3D"prop%3Apropertiesdotproduct"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Let \(k\) and \(p\) denote scalars and \(\vec{u}=
,\vec{v},\vec{w}\) denote vectors. Then the dot product \(\vec{u} \bullet \=
vec{v}\) satisfies the following properties.</p>

<ul>
    <li class=3D"lt-math-21265">\(\vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}=3D \vec{v}\bullet =
\vec{u}\)</li>
    <li class=3D"lt-math-21265">\(\vec{u}\bullet \vec{u}\geq 0 \text{ and e=
quals zero if and only if }\vec{u}=3D\vec{0}\)</li>
    <li class=3D"lt-math-21265">\(\left( k\vec{u}+p\vec{v}\right) \bullet \=
vec{w}=3Dk\left( \vec{u}\bullet \vec{w}\right) +p\left( \vec{v}\bullet \vec=
{w}\right)\)</li>
    <li class=3D"lt-math-21265">\(\vec{u}\bullet\left( k\vec{v}+p\vec{w}\ri=
ght) =3Dk\left( \vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}\right) +p\left( \vec{u}\bullet \vec{=
w}\right)\)</li>
    <li class=3D"lt-math-21265">\(\| \vec{u}\| ^{2}=3D\vec{u}\bullet \vec{u=
}\)</li>
</ul>

<dl>
    <dt><strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Proof</strong></dt>
    <dd>
    <p class=3D"lt-math-21265">The proof is left as an exercise.</p>
    </dd>
</dl>
</div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">This proposition tells us that we can also use t=
he dot product to find the length of a vector.</p>

<section class=3D"box-example">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Example_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B2.7D.5C):_Length_of_a_Vector"></span><h5=
 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-icon-default">Example \(\P=
ageIndex{2}\): <span>Length of a </span>Vector <a name=3D"exa%3Adotproductl=
ength"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Find the length of \[\vec{u} =3D \left[ \begin{a=
rray}{r} 2 \\ 1 \\ 4 \\ 2 \end{array} \right]\nonumber \] That is, find \(\=
| \vec{u} \| .\)</p>

<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Solution_2"></span><h6 class=3D"lt-math-21265 editable">Solution</h=
6>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">By <a title=3D"4.7: The Dot Product" class=3D"mt=
-self-link" href=3D"https://math.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/=
A_First_Course_in_Linear_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3A_R/4.07%3A_The_Dot_Product#=
prop:propertiesdotproduct" rel=3D"internal">Proposition \(\PageIndex{1}\)</=
a>, \(\| \vec{u} \| ^{2} =3D \vec{u} \bullet \vec{u}\). Therefore, \(\| \ve=
c{u} \| =3D \sqrt {\vec{u} \bullet \vec{u}}\). First, compute \(\vec{u} \bu=
llet \vec{u}\).</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">This is given by \[\begin{aligned} \vec{u} \bull=
et \vec{u} &amp;=3D (2)(2) + (1)(1) + (4)(4) + (2)(2) \\ &amp;=3D 4 + 1 + 1=
6 + 4 \\ &amp;=3D 25\end{aligned}\]</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Then, \[\begin{aligned} \| \vec{u} \| &amp;=3D \=
sqrt {\vec{u} \bullet \vec{u}} \\ &amp;=3D \sqrt{25} \\ &amp;=3D 5\end{alig=
ned}\]</p>
</div></div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">You may wish to compare this to our previous def=
inition of length, given in <a title=3D"4.4: Length of a Vector" href=3D"ht=
tps://math.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3A_R/4.04%3A_Length_of_a_Vector#def:lengthofvector"=
 rel=3D"internal">Definition 4.4.2</a>.</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">The <strong>Cauchy Schwarz inequality</strong> i=
s a fundamental inequality satisfied by the dot product. It is given in the=
 following theorem.</p>

<section class=3D"box-definition">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Theorem_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B1.7D.5C):_Cauchy_Schwarz_Inequality"></s=
pan><h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-icon-default">Theor=
em \(\PageIndex{1}\): <span>Cauchy Schwarz </span>Inequality <a name=3D"thm=
%3Acauchyschwarzinequality"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">The dot product satisfies the inequality \[\left=
\vert \vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}\right\vert \leq \| \vec{u}\| \| \vec{v}\| \lab=
el{cauchy}\] Furthermore equality is obtained if and only if one of \(\vec{=
u}\) or \(\vec{v}\) is a scalar multiple of the other.</p>

<dl>
    <dt><strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Proof</strong></dt>
    <dd>
    <p class=3D"lt-math-21265">First note that if \(\vec{v}=3D\vec{0}\) bot=
h sides of \(\eqref{cauchy}\) equal zero and so the inequality holds in thi=
s case. Therefore, it will be assumed in what follows that \(\vec{v}\neq \v=
ec{0}\).</p>

    <p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Define a function of \(t\in \mathbb{R}\) by =
\[f\left( t\right) =3D\left( \vec{u}+t\vec{v}\right) \bullet \left( \vec{u}=
+ t\vec{v}\right)\nonumber \] Then by <a title=3D"4.7: The Dot Product" cla=
ss=3D"mt-self-link" href=3D"https://math.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Linear_=
Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Linear_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3A_R/4.07%3A_The_Dot_=
Product#prop:propertiesdotproduct" rel=3D"internal">Proposition \(\PageInde=
x{1}\)</a>, \(f\left( t\right) \geq 0\) for all \(t\in \mathbb{R}\). Also f=
rom <a title=3D"4.7:  The Dot Product" class=3D"mt-self-link" href=3D"https=
://math.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Linear_=
Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3A_R/4.07%3A_The_Dot_Product#prop:propertiesdotproduct=
" rel=3D"internal">Proposition \(\PageIndex{1}\)</a> \[\begin{aligned} f\le=
ft( t\right) &amp;=3D\vec{u}\bullet \left( \vec{u}+t\vec{v}\right) + t\vec{=
v}\bullet \left( \vec{u}+t\vec{v}\right) \\ &amp;=3D\vec{u}\bullet \vec{u}+=
t\left( \vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}\right) + t \vec{v}\bullet \vec{u}+ t^{2}\vec=
{v}\bullet \vec{v} \\ &amp;=3D\| \vec{u}\| ^{2}+2t\left( \vec{u}\bullet \ve=
c{v}\right) +\| \vec{v}\| ^{2}t^{2}\end{aligned}\]</p>

    <p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Now this means the graph of \(y=3Df\left( t\=
right)\) is a parabola which opens up and either its vertex touches the \(t=
\) axis or else the entire graph is above the \(t\) axis. In the first case=
, there exists some \(t\) where \(f\left( t\right) =3D0\) and this requires=
 \(\vec{u}+t\vec{v}=3D\vec{0}\) so one vector is a multiple of the other. T=
hen clearly equality holds in \(\eqref{cauchy}\). In the case where \(\vec{=
v}\) is not a multiple of \(\vec{u}\), it follows \(f\left( t\right) &gt;0\=
) for all \(t\) which says \(f\left( t\right)\) has no real zeros and so fr=
om the quadratic formula, \[\left( 2\left( \vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}\right) \r=
ight) ^{2}-4\| \vec{u} \| ^{2}\| \vec{v}\| ^{2}&lt;0\nonumber \] which is e=
quivalent to \(\left\vert \vec{u}\bullet \vec{v} \right\vert &lt;\| \vec{u}=
\| \| \vec{v}\|\).</p>
    </dd>
</dl>
</div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Notice that this proof was based only on the pro=
perties of the dot product listed in <a title=3D"4.7: The Dot Product" clas=
s=3D"mt-self-link" href=3D"https://math.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Linear_A=
lgebra/A_First_Course_in_Linear_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3A_R/4.07%3A_The_Dot_P=
roduct#prop:propertiesdotproduct" rel=3D"internal">Proposition \(\PageIndex=
{1}\)</a>. This means that whenever an operation satisfies these properties=
, the Cauchy Schwarz inequality holds. There are many other instances of th=
ese properties besides vectors in \(\mathbb{R}^{n}\).</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">The Cauchy Schwarz inequality provides another p=
roof of the <strong>triangle inequality</strong> for distances in \(\mathbb=
{R}^{n}\).</p>

<section class=3D"box-definition">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Theorem_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B2.7D.5C):_Triangle_Inequality"></span><h=
5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-icon-default">Theorem \(\=
PageIndex{2}\): <span>Triangle </span>Inequality <a name=3D"thm%3Atrianglei=
nequalitydotproduct"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">For \(\vec{u},\vec{v}\in \mathbb{R}^{n}\) \[\| \=
vec{u}+\vec{v}\| \leq \| \vec{u}\| +\| \vec{v} \| \label{triangleineq1}\] a=
nd equality holds if and only if one of the vectors is a non-negative scala=
r multiple of the other.</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Also \[\| \| \vec{u}\| -\| \vec{v}\| \| \leq \| =
\vec{u}-\vec{v}\| \label{triangleineq2}\]</p>

<dl>
    <dt><strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Proof</strong></dt>
    <dd>
    <p class=3D"lt-math-21265">By properties of the dot product and the Cau=
chy Schwarz inequality, \[\begin{aligned} \| \vec{u}+\vec{v}\| ^{2} &amp;=
=3D \left( \vec{u}+\vec{v}\right) \bullet \left( \vec{u}+\vec{v}\right) \\ =
&amp; =3D\left( \vec{u}\bullet \vec{u}\right) +\left( \vec{u}\bullet \vec{v=
}\right) +\left(\vec{v}\bullet \vec{u}\right) +\left( \vec{v}\bullet \vec{v=
}\right) \\ &amp;=3D\| \vec{u}\| ^{2}+2\left( \vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}\right)=
+\| \vec{v}\| ^{2} \\ &amp;\leq \| \vec{u}\| ^{2}+2\left\vert \vec{u}\bulle=
t \vec{v}\right\vert +\| \vec{v}\| ^{2} \\ &amp;\leq \| \vec{u}\| ^{2}+2\| =
\vec{u}\| \| \vec{v}\| +\| \vec{v}\| ^{2} =3D\left( \| \vec{u}\| +\| \vec{v=
}\|\right) ^{2}\end{aligned}\] Hence, \[\| \vec{u}+\vec{v}\| ^{2} \leq \lef=
t( \| \vec{u}\| +\| \vec{v}\| \right) ^{2}\nonumber \] Taking square roots =
of both sides you obtain \(\eqref{triangleineq1}\).</p>

    <p class=3D"lt-math-21265">It remains to consider when equality occurs.=
 Suppose \(\vec{u} =3D \vec{0}\). Then, \(\vec{u} =3D 0 \vec{v}\) and the c=
laim about when equality occurs is verified. The same argument holds if \(\=
vec{v} =3D \vec{0}\). Therefore, it can be assumed both vectors are nonzero=
. To get equality in \(\eqref{triangleineq1}\) above, <a title=3D"4.7: The =
Dot Product" class=3D"mt-self-link" href=3D"https://math.libretexts.org/Boo=
kshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Linear_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3A_R/=
4.07%3A_The_Dot_Product#thm:cauchyschwarzinequality" rel=3D"internal">Theor=
em \(\PageIndex{1}\)</a> implies one of the vectors must be a multiple of t=
he other. Say \(\vec{v}=3D k \vec{u}\). If \(k &lt;0\) then equality cannot=
 occur in \(\eqref{triangleineq1}\) because in this case \[\vec{u}\bullet \=
vec{v} =3Dk \| \vec{u}\| ^{2}&lt;0&lt;\left| k \right| \| \vec{u}\| ^{2}=3D=
\left| \vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}\right|\nonumber \] Therefore, \(k \geq 0.\)</=
p>

    <p class=3D"lt-math-21265">To get the other form of the triangle inequa=
lity write \[\vec{u}=3D\vec{u}-\vec{v}+\vec{v}\nonumber \] so \[\begin{alig=
ned} \| \vec{u}\| &amp; =3D\| \vec{u}-\vec{v}+\vec{v}\| \\ &amp; \leq \| \v=
ec{u}-\vec{v}\| +\| \vec{v}\| \end{aligned}\] Therefore, \[\| \vec{u}\| -\|=
 \vec{v}\| \leq \| \vec{u}-\vec{v} \| \label{triangleineq3}\] Similarly, \[=
\| \vec{v}\| -\| \vec{u}\| \leq \| \vec{v}-\vec{u} \| =3D\| \vec{u}-\vec{v}=
\| \label{triangleineq4}\] It follows from \(\eqref{triangleineq3}\) and \(=
\eqref{triangleineq4}\) that \(\eqref{triangleineq2}\) holds. This is becau=
se \(\left| \| \vec{u}\| -\| \vec{v}\| \right|\) equals the left side of ei=
ther \(\eqref{triangleineq3}\) or \(\eqref{triangleineq4}\) and either way,=
 \(\left| \| \vec{u}\| -\| \vec{v}\| \right| \leq \| \vec{u}-\vec{v}\|\).</=
p>
    </dd>
</dl>
</div></section>

</div><div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_i=
n_Linear_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section=
" id=3D"section_2"><span id=3D"The_Geometric_Significance_of_the_Dot_Produc=
t"></span><h2 class=3D"lt-math-21265 editable">The Geometric Significance o=
f the Dot Product</h2>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Given two vectors, \(\vec{u}\) and \(\vec{v}\), =
the <strong>included angle</strong> is the angle between these two vectors =
which is given by \(\theta\) such that \(0 \leq \theta \leq \pi\). The dot =
product can be used to determine the included angle between two vectors. Co=
nsider the following picture where \(\theta\) gives the included angle.</p>

<figure><img alt=3D"two vectors u and v, with the angle between the vectors=
 labeled theta" class=3D"internal default" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://=
math.libretexts.org/@api/deki/files/75097/clipboard_eb05464df3a85a9ce9705bc=
512d33a33a.png?revision=3D1">
<figcaption>Figure \(\PageIndex{1}\)</figcaption>
</figure>

<section class=3D"box-definition">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Proposition_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B2.7D.5C):_The_Dot_Product_and_the_In=
cluded_Angle"></span><h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-ic=
on-default">Proposition \(\PageIndex{2}\): <span>The Dot Product and the In=
cluded </span>Angle <a name=3D"prop%3Adotproductangle"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Let \(\vec{u}\) and \(\vec{v}\) be two vectors i=
n \(\mathbb{R}^n\), and let \(\theta\) be the included angle. Then the foll=
owing equation holds. \[\vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}=3D\| \vec{u}\| \| \vec{v} \|=
 \cos \theta\nonumber \]</p>
</div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">In words, the dot product of two vectors equals =
the product of the magnitude (or length) of the two vectors multiplied by t=
he cosine of the included angle. Note this gives a geometric description of=
 the dot product which does not depend explicitly on the coordinates of the=
 vectors.</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Consider the following example.</p>

<section class=3D"box-example">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Example_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B3.7D.5C):_Find_the_Angle_Between_Two_Vec=
tors"></span><h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-icon-defau=
lt">Example \(\PageIndex{3}\): <span>Find the Angle Between Two </span>Vect=
ors <a name=3D"exa%3Aangletwovectors"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Find the angle between the vectors given by \[\v=
ec{u} =3D \left[ \begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 1 \\ -1 \end{array} \right], \vec{v}=
 =3D \left[ \begin{array}{r} 3 \\ 4 \\ 1 \end{array} \right]\nonumber \]</p=
>

<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Solution_3"></span><h6 class=3D"lt-math-21265 editable">Solution</h=
6>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">By <a title=3D"4.7: The Dot Product" class=3D"mt=
-self-link" href=3D"https://math.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/=
A_First_Course_in_Linear_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3A_R/4.07%3A_The_Dot_Product#=
prop:dotproductangle" rel=3D"internal">Proposition \(\PageIndex{2}\)</a>, \=
[\vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}=3D\| \vec{u}\| \| \vec{v} \| \cos \theta\nonumber \=
] Hence, \[\cos \theta =3D\frac{\vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}}{\| \vec{u}\| \| \ve=
c{v} \|}\nonumber \]</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">First, we can compute \(\vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}\)=
. By <a title=3D"4.7: The Dot Product" class=3D"mt-self-link" href=3D"https=
://math.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Linear_=
Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3A_R/4.07%3A_The_Dot_Product#def:dotproductdefn" rel=
=3D"internal">Definition \(\PageIndex{1}\)</a>, this equals \[\vec{u}\bulle=
t \vec{v} =3D (2)(3) + (1)(4)+(-1)(1) =3D 9\nonumber \]</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Then, \[\begin{array}{c} \| \vec{u} \| =3D \sqrt=
{(2)(2)+(1)(1)+(1)(1)}=3D\sqrt{6}\\ \| \vec{v} \| =3D \sqrt{(3)(3)+(4)(4)+(=
1)(1)}=3D\sqrt{26} \end{array}\nonumber \] Therefore, the cosine of the inc=
luded angle equals \[\cos \theta =3D\frac{9}{\sqrt{26}\sqrt{6}}=3D0.7205766=
...\nonumber \]</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">With the cosine known, the angle can be determin=
ed by computing the inverse cosine of that angle, giving approximately \(\t=
heta =3D0.76616\) radians.</p>
</div></div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Another application of the geometric description=
 of the dot product is in finding the angle between two lines. Typically on=
e would assume that the lines intersect. In some situations, however, it ma=
y make sense to ask this question when the lines do not intersect, such as =
the angle between two object trajectories. In any case we understand it to =
mean the smallest angle between (any of) their direction vectors. The only =
subtlety here is that if \(\vec{u}\) is a direction vector for a line, then=
 so is any multiple \(k\vec{u}\), and thus we will find complementary angle=
s among all angles between direction vectors for two lines, and we simply t=
ake the smaller of the two.</p>

<section class=3D"box-example">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Example_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B4.7D.5C):_Find_the_Angle_Between_Two_Lin=
es"></span><h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-icon-default=
">Example \(\PageIndex{4}\): <span>Find the Angle Between Two </span>Lines =
<a name=3D"exa%3Aanglebetweentwolines"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Find the angle between the two lines \[L_1: \; \=
left[ \begin{array}{r} x \\ y \\ z \end{array} \right] =3D \left[ \begin{ar=
ray}{r} 1 \\ 2 \\ 0 \end{array} \right] +t\left[ \begin{array}{r} -1 \\ 1 \=
\ 2 \end{array} \right]\nonumber \] and \[L_2: \; \left[ \begin{array}{r} x=
 \\ y \\ z \end{array} \right] =3D \left[ \begin{array}{r} 0 \\ 4 \\ -3 \en=
d{array} \right] +s\left[ \begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 1 \\ -1 \end{array} \right]=
\nonumber \]</p>

<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Solution_4"></span><h6 class=3D"lt-math-21265 editable">Solution</h=
6>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">You can verify that these lines do not intersect=
, but as discussed above this does not matter and we simply find the smalle=
st angle between any directions vectors for these lines.</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">To do so we first find the angle between the dir=
ection vectors given above: \[\vec{u}=3D\left[ \begin{array}{r} -1 \\ 1 \\ =
2 \end{array} \right],\; \vec{v}=3D\left[ \begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 1 \\ -1 \en=
d{array} \right]\nonumber \]</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">In order to find the angle, we solve the followi=
ng equation for \(\theta\) \[\vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}=3D\| \vec{u}\| \| \vec{=
v} \| \cos \theta\nonumber \] to obtain \(\cos \theta =3D -\frac{1}{2}\) an=
d since we choose included angles between \(0\) and \(\pi\) we obtain \(\th=
eta =3D \frac{2 \pi}{3}\).</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Now the angles between any two direction vectors=
 for these lines will either be \(\frac{2 \pi}{3}\) or its complement \(\ph=
i =3D \pi - \frac{2 \pi}{3} =3D \frac{\pi}{3}\). We choose the smaller angl=
e, and therefore conclude that the angle between the two lines is \(\frac{\=
pi}{3}\).</p>
</div></div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">We can also use <a title=3D"4.7: The Dot Product=
" class=3D"mt-self-link" href=3D"https://math.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Li=
near_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Linear_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3A_R/4.07%3A_The=
_Dot_Product#prop:dotproductangle" rel=3D"internal">Proposition \(\PageInde=
x{2}\)</a> to compute the dot product of two vectors.</p>

<section class=3D"box-example">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Example_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B5.7D.5C):_Using_Geometric_Description_to=
_Find_a_Dot_Product"></span><h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=
=3D"lt-icon-default">Example \(\PageIndex{5}\): <span>Using Geometric Descr=
iption to Find a Dot </span>Product <a name=3D"exa%3Ageometricdotproduct"><=
/a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Let \(\vec{u},\vec{v}\) be vectors with \(\| \ve=
c{u} \| =3D 3\) and \(\| \vec{v} \| =3D 4\). Suppose the angle between \(\v=
ec{u}\) and \(\vec{v}\) is \(\pi / 3\). Find \(\vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}\).</p=
>

<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Solution_5"></span><h6 class=3D"lt-math-21265 editable">Solution</h=
6>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">From the geometric description of the dot produc=
t in <a title=3D"4.7: The Dot Product" class=3D"mt-self-link" href=3D"https=
://math.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Linear_=
Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3A_R/4.07%3A_The_Dot_Product#prop:dotproductangle" rel=
=3D"internal">Proposition \(\PageIndex{2}\)</a> \[\vec{u}\bullet \vec{v}=3D=
(3)(4) \cos \left( \pi / 3\right) =3D3\times 4\times 1/2=3D6\nonumber \]</p=
>
</div></div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Two nonzero vectors are said to be <strong>perpe=
ndicular</strong>, sometimes also called <strong>orthogonal</strong>, if th=
e included angle is \(\pi /2\) radians (\(90^{\circ }).\)</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Consider the following proposition.</p>

<section class=3D"box-definition">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Proposition_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B3.7D.5C):_Perpendicular_Vectors"></s=
pan><h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-icon-default">Propo=
sition \(\PageIndex{3}\): <span>Perpendicular </span>Vectors <a name=3D"pro=
p%3Aperpvectors"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Let \(\vec{u}\) and \(\vec{v}\) be nonzero vecto=
rs in \(\mathbb{R}^n\). Then, \(\vec{u}\) and \(\vec{v}\) are said to be <s=
trong>perpendicular</strong> exactly when \[\vec{u} \bullet \vec{v} =3D 0\n=
onumber \]</p>

<dl>
    <dt><strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Proof</strong></dt>
    <dd>
    <p class=3D"lt-math-21265">This follows directly from <a title=3D"4.7: =
The Dot Product" class=3D"mt-self-link" href=3D"https://math.libretexts.org=
/Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Linear_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3=
A_R/4.07%3A_The_Dot_Product#prop:dotproductangle" rel=3D"internal">Proposit=
ion \(\PageIndex{2}\)</a>. First if the dot product of two nonzero vectors =
is equal to \(0\), this tells us that \(\cos \theta =3D0\) (this is where w=
e need nonzero vectors). Thus \(\theta =3D \pi /2\) and the vectors are per=
pendicular.</p>

    <p class=3D"lt-math-21265">If on the other hand \(\vec{v}\) is perpendi=
cular to \(\vec{u}\), then the included angle is \(\pi /2\) radians. Hence =
\(\cos \theta =3D0\) and \(\vec{u} \bullet \vec{v} =3D 0\).</p>
    </dd>
</dl>
</div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Consider the following example.</p>

<section class=3D"box-example">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Example_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B6.7D.5C):_Determine_if_Two_Vectors_are_P=
erpendicular"></span><h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-ic=
on-default">Example \(\PageIndex{6}\): <span>Determine if Two Vectors are <=
/span>Perpendicular <a name=3D"exa%3Aperpendicularvectors"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Determine whether the two vectors, \[\vec{u}=3D =
\left[ \begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 1 \\ -1 \end{array} \right], \vec{v} =3D \left=
[ \begin{array}{r} 1 \\ 3 \\ 5 \end{array} \right]\nonumber \] are perpendi=
cular.</p>

<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Solution_6"></span><h6 class=3D"lt-math-21265 editable">Solution</h=
6>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">In order to determine if these two vectors are p=
erpendicular, we compute the dot product. This is given by \[\vec{u} \bulle=
t \vec{v} =3D (2)(1) + (1)(3) + (-1)(5) =3D 0\nonumber \] Therefore, by <a =
title=3D"4.7: The Dot Product" class=3D"mt-self-link" href=3D"https://math.=
libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Linear_Algebra_=
(Kuttler)/04%3A_R/4.07%3A_The_Dot_Product#prop:perpvectors" rel=3D"internal=
">Proposition \(\PageIndex{3}\)</a> these two vectors are perpendicular.</p=
>
</div></div></section>

</div><div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_i=
n_Linear_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section=
" id=3D"section_3"><span id=3D"Projections"></span><h2 class=3D"lt-math-212=
65 editable">Projections</h2>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">In some applications, we wish to write a vector =
as a sum of two related vectors. Through the concept of projections, we can=
 find these two vectors. First, we explore an important theorem. The result=
 of this theorem will provide our definition of a vector projection.</p>

<section class=3D"box-definition">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Theorem_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B3.7D.5C):_Vector_Projections"></span><h5=
 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-icon-default">Theorem \(\P=
ageIndex{3}\): <span>Vector </span>Projections <a name=3D"thm%3Aprojection"=
></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Let \(\vec{v}\) and \(\vec{u}\) be nonzero vecto=
rs. Then there exist unique vectors \(\vec{v}_{||}\) and \(\vec{v}_{\bot }\=
) such that \[\vec{v}=3D\vec{v}_{||}+\vec{v}_{\bot } \label{projection}\] w=
here \(\vec{v}_{||}\) is a scalar multiple of \(\vec{u}\), and \(\vec{v}_{\=
bot}\) is perpendicular to \(\vec{u}\).</p>

<dl>
    <dt><strong class=3D"emphasis bold">Proof</strong></dt>
    <dd>
    <p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Suppose \(\eqref{projection}\) holds and \(\=
vec{v}_{||}=3D k \vec{u}\). Taking the dot product of both sides of \(\eqre=
f{projection}\) with \(\vec{u}\) and using \(\vec{v}_{\bot }\bullet \vec{u}=
=3D0,\) this yields \[\begin{array}{ll} \vec{v}\bullet \vec{u} &amp; =3D ( =
\vec{v}_{||}+\vec{v}_{\bot }) \bullet \vec{u} \\ &amp; =3D k\vec{u} \bullet=
 \vec{u} + \vec{v}_{\bot} \bullet \vec{u} \\ &amp; =3D k \| \vec{u}\| ^{2} =
\end{array}\nonumber \] which requires \(k =3D\vec{v}\bullet \vec{u} / \| \=
vec{u}\| ^{2}.\) Thus there can be no more than one vector \(\vec{v}_{||}\)=
. It follows \(\vec{v}_{\bot }\) must equal \(\vec{v}-\vec{v}_{||}.\) This =
verifies there can be no more than one choice for both \(\vec{v}_{||}\) and=
 \(\vec{v}_{\bot }\) and proves their uniqueness.</p>

    <p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Now let \[\vec{v}_{||} =3D \frac{\vec{v}\bul=
let \vec{u}}{\| \vec{u}\| ^{2}}\vec{u}\nonumber \] and let \[\vec{v}_{\bot =
}=3D\vec{v}-\vec{v}_{||}=3D\vec{v}-\frac{\vec{v}\bullet \vec{u}} {\| \vec{u=
}\| ^{2}}\vec{u}\nonumber \] Then \(\vec{v}_{||}=3D k\vec{u}\) where \(k =
=3D\frac{\vec{v}\bullet \vec{u}}{\| \vec{u}\| ^{2}}\). It only remains to v=
erify \(\vec{v}_{\bot }\bullet \vec{u}=3D0.\) But \[\begin{aligned} \vec{v}=
_{\bot }\bullet \vec{u} &amp;=3D \vec{v}\bullet \vec{u}-\frac{\vec{v}\bulle=
t \vec{u}}{\| \vec{u}\| ^{2}}\vec{u}\bullet \vec{u} \\ &amp;=3D \vec{v}\bul=
let\vec{u}-\vec{v}\bullet \vec{u}\\ &amp;=3D 0 \end{aligned}\]</p>
    </dd>
</dl>
</div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">The vector \(\vec{v}_{||}\) in <a title=3D"4.7: =
The Dot Product" class=3D"mt-self-link" href=3D"https://math.libretexts.org=
/Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Linear_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04%3=
A_R/4.07%3A_The_Dot_Product#thm:projection" rel=3D"internal">Theorem \(\Pag=
eIndex{3}\)</a> is called the <strong>projection</strong> of \(\vec{v}\) on=
to \(\vec{u}\) and is denoted by \[\vec{v}_{||} =3D \mathrm{proj}_{\vec{u}}=
\left( \vec{v}\right)\nonumber \]</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">We now make a formal definition of the vector pr=
ojection.</p>

<section class=3D"box-definition">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Definition_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B2.7D.5C):_Vector_Projection"></span><=
h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-icon-default">Definition=
 \(\PageIndex{2}\): <span>Vector </span>Projection <a name=3D"def%3Aproject=
ion"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Let \(\vec{u}\) and \(\vec{v}\) be vectors. Then=
, the <strong>projection of \(\vec{v}\) onto \(\vec{u}\)</strong> is given =
by \[\mathrm{proj}_{\vec{u}}\left( \vec{v}\right) =3D\left( \frac{\vec{v}\b=
ullet \vec{u}}{\vec{u}\bullet \vec{u}}\right) \vec{u} =3D \frac{\vec{v}\bul=
let \vec{u}}{\| \vec{u}\| ^{2}}\vec{u}\nonumber \]</p>
</div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Consider the following example of a projection.<=
/p>

<section class=3D"box-example">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Example_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B7.7D.5C):_Find_the_Projection_of_One_Vec=
tor_Onto_Another"></span><h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"l=
t-icon-default">Example \(\PageIndex{7}\): <span>Find the Projection of One=
 Vector Onto </span>Another <a name=3D"exa%3Avectorprojection"></a></span><=
/h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Find \(\mathrm{proj}_{\vec{u}}\left( \vec{v}\rig=
ht)\) if \[\vec{u}=3D \left[ \begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 3 \\ -4 \end{array} \rig=
ht], \vec{v}=3D \left[ \begin{array}{r} 1 \\ -2 \\ 1 \end{array} \right]\no=
number \]</p>

<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Solution_7"></span><h6 class=3D"lt-math-21265 editable">Solution</h=
6>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">We can use the formula provided in <a title=3D"4=
.7: The Dot Product" class=3D"mt-self-link" href=3D"https://math.libretexts=
.org/Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Linear_Algebra_(Kuttler)/=
04%3A_R/4.07%3A_The_Dot_Product#def:projection" rel=3D"internal">Definition=
 \(\PageIndex{2}\)</a> to find \(\mathrm{proj}_{\vec{u}}\left( \vec{v}\righ=
t)\). First, compute \(\vec{v} \bullet \vec{u}\). This is given by \[\begin=
{aligned} \left[ \begin{array}{r} 1 \\ -2 \\ 1 \end{array} \right] \bullet =
\left[ \begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 3 \\ -4 \end{array} \right] &amp;=3D (2)(1) + =
(3)(-2) + (-4)(1) \\ &amp;=3D 2 - 6 - 4 \\ &amp;=3D -8\end{aligned}\] Simil=
arly, \(\vec{u} \bullet \vec{u}\) is given by \[\begin{aligned} \left[ \beg=
in{array}{r} 2 \\ 3 \\ -4 \end{array} \right] \bullet \left[ \begin{array}{=
r} 2 \\ 3 \\ -4 \end{array} \right] &amp;=3D (2)(2) + (3)(3) + (-4)(-4) \\ =
&amp;=3D 4 + 9 + 16 \\ &amp;=3D 29\end{aligned}\]</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Therefore, the projection is equal to \[\begin{a=
ligned} \mathrm{proj}_{\vec{u}}\left( \vec{v}\right) &amp;=3D-\frac{8}{29} =
\left[ \begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 3 \\ -4 \end{array} \right] \\ &amp;=3D \left[=
 \begin{array}{r} - \frac{16}{29} \\ - \frac{24}{29} \\ \frac{32}{29} \end{=
array} \right]\end{aligned}\]</p>
</div></div></section>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">We will conclude this section with an important =
application of projections. Suppose a line \(L\) and a point \(P\) are give=
n such that \(P\) is not contained in \(L\). Through the use of projections=
, we can determine the shortest distance from \(P\) to \(L\).</p>

<section class=3D"box-example">
<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Example_.5C(.5CPageIndex.7B8.7D.5C):_Shortest_Distance_from_a_Point=
_to_a_Line"></span><h5 class=3D"box-legend editable"><span class=3D"lt-icon=
-default">Example \(\PageIndex{8}\): <span>Shortest Distance from a Point t=
o a </span>Line <a name=3D"exa%3Ashortestpointline"></a></span></h5>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Let \(P =3D (1,3,5)\) be a point in \(\mathbb{R}=
^3\), and let \(L\) be the line which goes through point \(P_0 =3D (0,4,-2)=
\) with direction vector \(\vec{d} =3D \left[ \begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 1 \\ 2 =
\end{array} \right]\). Find the shortest distance from \(P\) to the line \(=
L\), and find the point \(Q\) on \(L\) that is closest to \(P\).</p>

<div mt-section-origin=3D"Bookshelves/Linear_Algebra/A_First_Course_in_Line=
ar_Algebra_(Kuttler)/04:_R/4.07:_The_Dot_Product" class=3D"mt-section"><spa=
n id=3D"Solution_8"></span><h6 class=3D"lt-math-21265 editable">Solution</h=
6>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">In order to determine the shortest distance from=
 \(P\) to \(L\), we will first find the vector \(\overrightarrow{P_0P}\) an=
d then find the projection of this vector onto \(L\). The vector \(\overrig=
htarrow{P_0P}\) is given by \[\left[ \begin{array}{r} 1 \\ 3 \\ 5 \end{arra=
y} \right] - \left[ \begin{array}{r} 0 \\ 4 \\ -2 \end{array} \right] =3D \=
left[ \begin{array}{r} 1 \\ -1 \\ 7 \end{array} \right]\nonumber \]</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Then, if \(Q\) is the point on \(L\) closest to =
\(P\), it follows that \[\begin{aligned} \overrightarrow{P_0Q} &amp;=3D \ma=
thrm{proj}_{\vec{d}}\overrightarrow{P_0P} \\ &amp;=3D \left( \frac{ \overri=
ghtarrow{P_0P}\bullet \vec{d}}{\|\vec{d}\|^2}\right) \vec{d} \\ &amp;=3D \f=
rac{15}{9} \left[ \begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 1 \\ 2 \end{array} \right] \\ &amp;=
=3D \frac{5}{3} \left[ \begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 1 \\ 2 \end{array} \right]\end=
{aligned}\]</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Now, the distance from \(P\) to \(L\) is given b=
y \[\| \overrightarrow{QP} \| =3D \| \overrightarrow{P_0P} - \overrightarro=
w{P_0Q}\| =3D \sqrt{26}\nonumber \]</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">The point \(Q\) is found by adding the vector \(=
\overrightarrow{P_0Q}\) to the position vector \(\overrightarrow{0P_0}\) fo=
r \(P_0\) as follows \[\begin{aligned} \left[ \begin{array}{r} 0 \\ 4 \\ -2=
 \end{array} \right] + \frac{5}{3} \left[ \begin{array}{r} 2 \\ 1 \\ 2 \end=
{array} \right] &amp;=3D \left[ \begin{array}{r} \frac{10}{3} \\ \frac{17}{=
3} \\ \frac{4}{3} \end{array} \right]\end{aligned}\]</p>

<p class=3D"lt-math-21265">Therefore, \(Q =3D (\frac{10}{3}, \frac{17}{3}, =
\frac{4}{3})\).</p>
</div></div></section>
</div>

